problem:
Arlene is to walk across a ``high wire" strung horizontally between two buildings 10.0 m apart. The sag in the rope when she is at the midpoint is 10.0$^\circ$, as shown in the diagram. If her mass is 50.0 kg, what is the tension in the rope at this point?
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{rope}
\end{center}

A 20.0-kg box rests on a table. (a) What is the weight of the box and the normal force acting on it? (b) A 10.0-kg box is placed on top of the 20.0-kg box, as shown in the figure. Determine the normal force that the table exerts on the 20.0-kg box and the normal force that the 20.0-kg box exerts on the 10.0-kg box.
    \begin{center}
    \includegraphics[scale=0.25]{boxes}
\end{center}

solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item The weight of the box is just $F_g=mg=20\cdot 9.8=196\, \unit N$, and the normal force is the exact same.
        \item Think of the two boxes as one big box of mass 30 kg. Thus the normal force between the table and the two boxes is just $N=30\cdot 9.8=294\, \unit N$. The normal force the 20 kg box exerts on the 10 kg box is just the force needed to support the weight of the 10 kg, which is $N=10\cdot 9.8=98\, \unit N$.
    \end{anum}

\begin{anum}
        \item By Newton's Third Law, the starting block exerts a force 720 N on the sprinter. The horizontal component of this force is $F_x=720\cos(22^\circ)=668\, \unit N$ so the horizontal acceleration is just $a_x=F_x/m=10.3\, \unit{m/s^2}$. 
        \item We have $\Delta v=a\Delta t=10.3\cdot 0.32=3.30 \unit{m/s}$. 
    \end{anum}

problem:
A box weighing 77.0 N rests on a table. A rope tied to the box runs vertically upward over a pulley and a weight is hung from the other end. Determine the force that the table exerts on the box if the weight hanging on the other side of the pulley weighs (a) 30.0 N, (b) 60.0 N, and (c) 90.0 N.
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.25]{boxpulley}
    \end{center}

solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item The tension must balance the weight of the smaller mass, so in this case it is $T=30\, \unit N$. The normal force acting on the box is found via $N=mg-T=77-30=47\, \unit N$.
        \item In this case, $T=60 \unit N$, and $N=mg-T=17\, \unit N$.
        \item In this case, $T=90 \unit N$, and $N=mg-T=-13 \, \unit N$. We appear to have a problem, though, because the normal force can only ``push" and not "pull"! This means the box will lose contact with the table, so the normal force is in fact 0. This does make sense because now the weight is heavier than the box. 
    \end{anum}

